Kotlin, Jetpack Compose, and AI-native tooling are converging fast — here’s the roadmap that separates developers who adapt from those who fall behind.
Android development audibly rewrites its own rules every few years. We’re in one of those years again and when your stack is still 2023-y, you’re going to feel it soon.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Where We’re Headed
K2 is no longer just an experimental compiler — instead, it’s the default implementation and it really projects such as real multi-module. Together with context parameters ⇒ where old context receivers were used, Kotlin code is obtaining cleaner, boilerplate-less form:
// Scoped access without manual passing
context(UserSession)
fun loadDashboard(): Dashboard {
// currentUser is already available here
return dashboardRepository.fetchFor(currentUser)
}On the client side of things, Compose has matured into an infrastructure you would genuinely refer to as production-ready. You were taught sensory data until October 2023; Developers have CSS-grid-like control over complex screens with new layout primitives, and the shared element transitions just don’t feel like a hack anymore.
